    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-13T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-13T03:00:00-05:00" n="493"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d493">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11606: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-13T16:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 13, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 13—11:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>33. Please consult Commander-in-Chief and give him this message: <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Area covered by former British, Russian and German Concessions and
                            present French Concession at Hankow and including Butterfield and
                            Swire’s property adjoining custom house including bulk of foreign owned
                            and occupied property here. In this area Consulates and Embassy staffs
                            are now located. In river off this area are concentrated foreign naval
                            vessels of British, American, French and Italian nationality and foreign
                            flag river shipping. Recent events at Wuhu and Nanking have caused
                            considerable apprehension as no [<hi rend="italic">to</hi>?] safety of
                            this area where are concentrated not only most of permanent residents
                            but many foreign refugees from other parts of China. It would be
                            difficult to shift population or shipping elsewhere. It would relieve
                            present apprehension if assurance could be obtained from Japanese that
                            area in question including river front immediately adjoining would be
                            free of attacks. Could you consult with interested British, French and
                            Italian colleagues with a view to exploring possibility of obtaining
                            some assurance from Japanese military and naval commands at Shanghai
                            controlling operations in this area.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to Shanghai, repeated to Department and Peiping. Peiping please repeat to
                    Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
